<p>I‚Äôve now read three of them so far: <em>Zanoni</em> by Edward Bulwer-Lytton, <em>The Sailor Who Fell From Grace With The Sea</em> by Yukio Mishima, and most recently <em>Nights At The Circus</em> by Angela Carter. I didn‚Äôt like <em>The Sailor</em> and I didn‚Äôt even finished <em>Zanoni</em> (<a href="http://www.amazon.com/Zanoni-Edward-Bulwer-Lytton-ebook/dp/B0084A7YGQ/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1455465835&amp;sr=8-2&amp;keywords=zanoni">it‚Äôs free on Kindle</a> by the way), but <em>Nights at the Circus</em> was a real treat.</p>

<p>There‚Äôs a lot of color, performance, sadness, and female-ness in <em>Nights at the Circus</em>‚Äì ‚ÄúA luscious and gooey dessert of a book‚Ä¶ doled out in sinful proportions,‚Äù heralds <em>The Washington Post Book World</em>; ‚ÄúLoud, bawdy, and unabashedly sentimental,‚Äù wrote someone at the <em>Times</em>. I think those both seem pretty apt, especially the ‚Äúbawdy.‚Äù</p>

<p>I don‚Äôt know much about Bowie, but I also think it‚Äôs pretty easy to see why this book was one of his favorites.  For each of these books, it‚Äôs fun to imagine where he read them, how he heard of them, what he took from them.</p>

